         <listPerson>
            <person sex="2">
               <persName xml:lang="gez" xml:id="n1" type="birth">እሌኒ፡</persName>
               <persName xml:lang="gez" corresp="#n1" type="normalized">ʾƎleni</persName>
               <occupation type="political">governor</occupation>
               <faith type="EOTC"/>
               <nationality type="Ethiopia"/>
             
               <floruit notBefore="1682" notAfter="1708">She was a daughter of <persName ref="PRS10375Yohanne">
                     <roleName type="title">ʾaṣe</roleName>Yoḥannǝs I</persName> and a sister of <persName ref="PRS5616IyasuI"/>. 
                  She was a remarkable figure in Ethiopian political life during the last quarter of the 17th century.
                  She was brought to prominence by <persName ref="PRS5616IyasuI"/> who immediately after his coronation in <date>1682</date>
                  granted her the title of the govenor of <placeName ref="LOC5671Semen"/>. After <date>1685</date>
                  she held no official post at the court and led the usual life of Ethiopian women of the royal blood,
                  with one important exception: she actively interefered in religious disputes which rendered the Ethiopian 
                  Church an ardent adherent of the Qǝbāt doctrine. This adherance went smoothly during the reign of her brother
                  <persName ref="PRS5616IyasuI"/>, who himself seemed symphathetic to the doctrine, but when his son 
                  <roleName type="title">ʾaṣe</roleName>
                  <persName ref="PRS9152TaklaHa"/>
                  refused to proclaim the Qǝbāt faith as a state doctrine, ʾƎleni with her nephew- in-law 
                  <persName ref="PRS9592Tulluu"/> started a conspiracy in <date>1706</date>. 
                  The result was fatal for them:
                  <roleName type="title">daǧǧāzmāč</roleName>
                  <persName ref="PRS9592Tulluu"/> was blinded and exiled to <placeName ref="LOC6569Tegray"/> 
                  and ʾƎleni was exiled to <placeName ref="LOC5897Tankal">, where she died. </placeName>
                     </floruit>
               <death when="1708"/> 
            </person>
